entry.title: Orvasca sp. (1)
entry.content: Species (1) as per Moths of Victoria Part 2

entry.title: Poecilasthena sp. (2)
entry.content: As per Moths of Victoria Part 3.

entry.title: Rhuma spp.
entry.content: Scales on forewings worn. This species appears to inhabit cool temperate forest gullies in Vic.

entry.title: Endoxyla interlucens
entry.content: There is some confusion about the name interlucens which may be a more northern species.

entry.title: Endoxyla spp.
entry.content: This is also the female of the Undescribed species however there is a major loss of scales on the wings. It gives the appearance of brown colour and you can see the wing veins clearly. There is also some damage around the head area. Surprising she could still navigate.

entry.title: Endoxyla spp.
entry.content: This is the female of the undescribed species (same date and location).

entry.title: Paraterpna sp. (1)
entry.content: Species 1 as per Moths of Victoria Part 4

entry.title: Xenomusa monoda
entry.content: This genus is in Ennominae - no tribe assigned.

entry.title: Chrysolarentia sp. (2)
entry.content: Species 2 according to Moths of Victoria Part 3.

entry.title: Nataxa flavescens
entry.content: One egg on the sheet near this female. Shadow removed from beneath left forewing to make it more obvious. Moth was very restless - obviously not the expected place to lay eggs.
